---

<PageShell
  title="Czech Republic Freelancer Visa (Živnostenský list) 2026: Complete Insurance & Requirements Guide"
  description="Complete guide to Czech Republic's Freelancer Visa (Zivno). CRITICAL: Only PVZP or Maxima insurance accepted - SafetyWing, Cigna NOT valid. Low costs, Prague lifestyle, path to EU residency."
  headline="Czech Republic Freelancer Visa: Insurance & Requirements Guide"
  subheadline="Everything you need for the Czech Živnostenský list (Zivno) visa—CRITICAL: only PVZP or Maxima insurance accepted (international insurers like SafetyWing and Cigna are NOT valid), affordable Prague living, and path to EU permanent residency."
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Learn About Czech Insurance Requirements"
  ctaButtonHref="#insurance-requirements"
  heroImage="/images/countries/czech-republic-hero-bg.png"
>

  <!-- Trust Signals -->
  <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 mb-8 text-sm text-neutral-600">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Updated February 2026
    </span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Official Ministry of Interior
    </span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-red-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M18 10a8 8 0 11-16 0 8 8 0 0116 0zm-7 4a1 1 0 11-2 0 1 1 0 012 0zm-1-9a1 1 0 00-1 1v4a1 1 0 102 0V6a1 1 0 00-1-1z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      PVZP/Maxima Insurance ONLY
    </span>
  </div>

  <!-- Section: Overview -->
  <section id="overview" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Overview</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Czech Republic Freelancer Visa—officially the Živnostenský list (trade license) combined with a long-term visa—has become one of Europe's most popular pathways for digital nomads and self-employed professionals. Known informally as the "Zivno visa," it offers affordable living in Prague, one of Europe's most beautiful cities, with a clear path to EU permanent residency after 5 years.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
      <p class="text-red-800">
        <strong>CRITICAL: Insurance Restriction</strong><br />
        Czech Republic has STRICT insurance requirements. For the freelancer visa, you <strong>MUST</strong> have insurance from <strong>PVZP</strong> or <strong>Maxima</strong> ONLY. International insurance providers—SafetyWing, Cigna Global, Allianz Care, BUPA, World Nomads—are <strong>NOT ACCEPTED</strong>. Your visa WILL be rejected. This is non-negotiable.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Unlike many countries, Czech Republic has no minimum income requirement for this visa. Instead, you need to demonstrate sufficient savings (approximately €5,000-6,000) to support yourself while establishing your freelance business. This makes it accessible to freelancers at various income levels.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts: Czech Freelancer Visa (Zivno)</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-primary-800">
        <li>• <strong>Official name:</strong> Živnostenský list (Trade License) + Long-term visa/residence permit</li>
        <li>• <strong>Duration:</strong> 1 year initial, renewable for 2 years</li>
        <li>• <strong>Income requirement:</strong> None (must show ~€5,000-6,000 savings)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Health insurance:</strong> ONLY PVZP or Maxima accepted (€500-800/year)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Trade license fee:</strong> ~€30 (CZK 1,000)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Visa fee:</strong> ~€100 (CZK 2,500)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Processing time:</strong> 60-90 days</li>
        <li>• <strong>Path to residency:</strong> Permanent residence after 5 years</li>
        <li>• <strong>Popular cities:</strong> Prague, Brno</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Why Choose Czech Republic for Freelancing?</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>No income requirement:</strong> Unlike Spain or Portugal, no minimum monthly income needed</li>
      <li><strong>Low costs:</strong> Trade license only €30, visa €100, insurance €500-800/year</li>
      <li><strong>Affordable living:</strong> Prague offers Western quality at Eastern European prices</li>
      <li><strong>Established nomad community:</strong> Large expat scene, abundant coworking spaces</li>
      <li><strong>Central location:</strong> Easy access to all of Europe via trains and budget airlines</li>
      <li><strong>Path to EU residency:</strong> Permanent residence after 5 continuous years</li>
      <li><strong>Beautiful architecture:</strong> Prague is one of Europe's most stunning cities</li>
      <li><strong>Fast internet:</strong> Excellent connectivity throughout the country</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Quick Decision Guide -->
  <section id="quick-decision" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Quick Decision Guide</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Czech Republic is Right For You If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>You want affordable European living</li>
          <li>You can use PVZP or Maxima insurance (required)</li>
          <li>You want no minimum income requirement</li>
          <li>You have ~€5,000-6,000 in savings</li>
          <li>You want a path to EU permanent residency</li>
          <li>You can handle bureaucratic processes</li>
          <li>You appreciate history, architecture, and cafe culture</li>
          <li>You want central European location for travel</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Consider Other Options If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>You want to use SafetyWing or other international insurance (not accepted)</li>
          <li>You need fast visa processing (60-90 days here)</li>
          <li>You prefer everything in English (Czech bureaucracy can be challenging)</li>
          <li>You want warmer weather year-round</li>
          <li>You prefer simpler visa processes (Portugal D7, for example)</li>
          <li>You don't want to deal with trade license paperwork</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Why digital nomads love the Zivno:</strong> The combination of no income requirement, very low fees, affordable living, and path to permanent EU residence makes this one of Europe's most accessible long-term visa options. The strict insurance requirement is manageable once you know to use PVZP or Maxima.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Visa Requirements -->
  <section id="requirements" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Visa Requirements</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Czech freelancer visa process involves two steps: obtaining a trade license (Živnostenský list), then applying for a long-term visa at a Czech embassy. You must apply IN PERSON at the embassy—online applications are not accepted.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={requirementsColumns} rows={requirementsRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">The Trade License (Živnostenský list)</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Živnostenský list is a business license that authorizes you to operate as a self-employed freelancer in the Czech Republic. Most digital work falls under "free trades" (volná živnost) which require no special qualifications.
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Trade License Basics</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• <strong>Cost:</strong> ~€30 (CZK 1,000)</li>
          <li>• <strong>Processing:</strong> 1-5 business days</li>
          <li>• <strong>Application:</strong> Can use a representative</li>
          <li>• <strong>Requirements:</strong> Clean criminal record</li>
          <li>• <strong>Valid activities:</strong> IT, consulting, design, marketing, writing, most digital work</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How to Apply</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• Apply at Trade Licensing Office (Živnostenský úřad)</li>
          <li>• Can be done through a registered agent/representative before you arrive</li>
          <li>• Need Czech address (agent can provide this initially)</li>
          <li>• Obtain before your visa appointment</li>
          <li>• Keep the license—you'll need it for visa renewal</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Financial Requirements</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Unlike Spain or Portugal's Digital Nomad Visas which require proof of high income, Czech Republic has no minimum income requirement. Instead, you need to show sufficient savings—approximately €5,000-6,000 in your bank account.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-6">
      <p class="text-green-800">
        <strong>No income proof needed:</strong> You don't need to show contracts, invoices, or minimum monthly income. Just bank statements demonstrating sufficient savings to support yourself. This makes the Czech freelancer visa accessible to those just starting out.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Document Checklist</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li>Valid passport (6+ months validity, 2+ blank pages)</li>
      <li>Trade license (Živnostenský list)</li>
      <li>Proof of accommodation in Czech Republic (lease or agent confirmation)</li>
      <li>Bank statements showing ~€5,000-6,000 (3 months)</li>
      <li>Health insurance certificate from PVZP or Maxima ONLY</li>
      <li>Criminal record certificate (apostilled)</li>
      <li>Passport photos (35x45mm, white background)</li>
      <li>Completed application forms</li>
      <li>Sworn translations of all non-Czech documents</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-amber-800">
        <strong>Document verification:</strong> Many documents need apostille or superlegalization depending on your country. Criminal record certificates typically need apostille. Check with the Czech embassy for your country's specific requirements—this can take 2-4 weeks.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Insurance Requirements -->
  <section id="insurance-requirements" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Insurance Requirements</h2>

    <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-300 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-3">CRITICAL: Only PVZP or Maxima Insurance Accepted</h3>
      <p class="text-red-800 mb-4">
        Czech immigration law requires comprehensive health insurance from <strong>specific authorized providers</strong> for long-term visas. For the freelancer visa, <strong>ONLY PVZP (Pojišťovna VZP) and Maxima pojišťovna are accepted</strong>.
      </p>
      <p class="text-red-800 font-semibold">
        International insurers—SafetyWing, Cigna Global, Allianz Care, BUPA, World Nomads, IMG Global—are NOT valid and your visa WILL be rejected if you apply with these. This is the #1 reason applications fail.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-4">
      This is one of the strictest insurance requirements in Europe. Many expats learn this the hard way after purchasing SafetyWing or Cigna and having their visa application rejected. Don't make this mistake—purchase PVZP or Maxima BEFORE your embassy appointment.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">PVZP vs Maxima Comparison</h3>

    <ComparisonTable columns={insuranceColumns} rows={insuranceRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">International Insurers: NOT Accepted</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      To be absolutely clear, here are popular international insurers that are NOT accepted for the Czech freelancer visa:
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={internationalInsuranceColumns} rows={internationalInsuranceRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Insurance Coverage Requirements</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">What PVZP/Maxima Covers</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>Comprehensive inpatient care (hospitalization)</li>
          <li>Outpatient medical visits</li>
          <li>Emergency medical treatment</li>
          <li>Prescription medications</li>
          <li>Emergency dental treatment</li>
          <li>Ambulance services</li>
          <li>Emergency repatriation</li>
          <li>Coverage limit: CZK 2,000,000+</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Typical Limitations</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>Limited or no travel coverage outside Czech Republic</li>
          <li>Pre-existing conditions may have waiting periods</li>
          <li>Routine dental may not be covered</li>
          <li>Cosmetic procedures excluded</li>
          <li>Some elective treatments limited</li>
          <li>Maternity may have waiting period</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Supplementary travel insurance:</strong> Since PVZP and Maxima primarily cover you within Czech Republic, many expats add supplementary travel insurance (SafetyWing, World Nomads) for trips to other Schengen countries. This is fine as a supplement—just don't try to use it for your visa application.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Where to Purchase</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-2">PVZP (Pojišťovna VZP)</h4>
        <p class="text-green-800 mb-2">Website: <a href="https://www.pvzp.cz" class="underline">pvzp.cz</a></p>
        <p class="text-green-800">English version available. Can purchase online. They provide the insurance certificate you need for your visa application.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-2">Maxima pojišťovna</h4>
        <p class="text-green-800 mb-2">Website: <a href="https://www.maxi.cz" class="underline">maxi.cz</a></p>
        <p class="text-green-800">English version available. Online purchase possible. Often slightly cheaper than PVZP for similar coverage.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA Box -->
  <CTABox
    variant="highlight"
    title="Czech Visa Insurance: Only PVZP or Maxima Accepted"
    description="Don't risk visa rejection with international insurance. Purchase from pvzp.cz or maxi.cz before your embassy appointment."
    buttonText="View Insurance Requirements"
    buttonHref="#recommended-providers"
  />

  <!-- Section: Recommended Providers -->
  <section id="recommended-providers" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For Czech freelancer visa compliance, you have exactly two options: PVZP or Maxima. Both are accepted and provide similar comprehensive coverage. Choose based on price and any specific coverage details that matter to you.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Provider Recommendations by Situation</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">First-time Applicant</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Use PVZP or Maxima—either is fine. PVZP is slightly more established; Maxima is sometimes cheaper. Both are fully accepted. Purchase before your embassy appointment and bring the insurance certificate.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Frequent Traveler in Schengen</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Use PVZP or Maxima for visa compliance, then add supplementary travel insurance (SafetyWing or similar) for trips outside Czech Republic. PVZP/Maxima coverage is primarily within Czech Republic.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Pre-existing Conditions</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Contact PVZP and Maxima directly to discuss your situation. Both may have waiting periods or limitations for pre-existing conditions. Get clarity before purchasing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-amber-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Already Have International Insurance</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You still need PVZP or Maxima for the visa—your Cigna, Allianz, or SafetyWing will not be accepted. You can keep your international insurance as supplementary coverage if you wish.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

