  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why can I only use PVZP or Maxima insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Czech immigration law specifically requires comprehensive health insurance from providers authorized for long-term visa purposes. Only PVZP (Pojišťovna VZP) and Maxima pojišťovna meet these requirements. International insurers like SafetyWing, Cigna Global, Allianz Care, and BUPA are NOT on the approved list—regardless of how good their coverage is. This is non-negotiable and the #1 reason visa applications are rejected.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How much does the visa process cost in total?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The direct costs are: trade license ~€30, visa fee ~€100, insurance €500-800/year, translations €100-300, apostilles €50-150. Total: approximately €800-1,400 for the first year. If you use a visa agency (recommended), add €200-500. You also need ~€5,000-6,000 in savings to show, but you keep this money.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is there a minimum income requirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Unlike Spain or Portugal's Digital Nomad Visas, Czech Republic has no minimum monthly income requirement. You need to demonstrate sufficient savings (~€5,000-6,000) rather than ongoing income. This makes it accessible to freelancers at various income levels, including those just starting out.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long does the visa process take?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Processing takes 60-90 days from your embassy appointment—one of the longer waits in Europe. Add time for trade license (1 week), document preparation and apostilles (2-4 weeks), and embassy appointment scheduling (2-4 weeks). Total: 3-5 months from start to arrival. Don't book flights until you have the visa.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Czech?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not officially required, but bureaucracy is challenging without it. English is common in Prague's expat areas but limited in government offices. Using a visa agency (€200-500) is highly recommended if you don't speak Czech—they handle paperwork, translations, and communication with authorities.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get permanent residency after this visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. After 5 years of continuous legal residence on the freelancer visa, you can apply for permanent residence. This removes the need for visa renewals and gives you broader rights in Czech Republic and the EU. Many expats successfully make this transition.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

